<TITLE> Shafiq assures war crimes trials will be 'impartial' </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 21 (bdnews24.com)Law minister Shafiq Ahmed has assured the European Commission that the trial of 1971 war criminals in Bangladesh will be impartial, transparent and internationally accepted. The minister briefed reporters at secretariat after a meeting with a European delegation led by David Tirr, director general of external relations at the commission. Tirr said the liberation war was an internal affair, and it was for Bangladesh to hold the trials. "But this is a very important issue for Bangladesh," he added. Law minister Shafiq said, "We assured them trials would be transparent, impartial and internationally accepted." "Steps have been taken to pick skilled, experienced and honest people to undertake the investigation and prosecution." "The EC delegation has also been briefed about the government's steps towards independence of judiciary, curbing corruption and representation of the opposition in the parliamentary standing committee." Replying to a question related to the amendment of the International Crimes (Tribunal) Act, he said, "Comments have been sought from the Law Commission to solve some technical disputes." State minister for law Kamrul Islam, desk officer of the commission Genovena Hernandez, EC ambassador Stefen Frowein and first secretary Charles Whiteley were present in the meeting. bd
